  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_681520829" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/681520829" />
    <a title="Alyssa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5986819-alyssa"><img alt="Alyssa" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/681520829?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alyssa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alyssa" href="/user/show/5986819-alyssa">Alyssa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer681520829" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12843217814523454280">This is my favorite canticle of the Divina Commedia. Sure, it&apos;s not as thrilling or fascinatingly grotesque (/grotesquely fascinating) as the Inferno, but the literary images are breathtakingly beautiful, not to mention extremely powerful. As a modern reader, it&apos;s hard not to be moved by Dante&apos;s poetry, even 7 centuries later, a fact that attests to the immortality of the work. Those who are unfamiliar with Dante and/or Italian Literature and stop reading the Commedia after the Inferno are missi</span>
  <span id="freeText12843217814523454280" style="display:none">This is my favorite canticle of the Divina Commedia. Sure, it's not as thrilling or fascinatingly grotesque (/grotesquely fascinating) as the Inferno, but the literary images are breathtakingly beautiful, not to mention extremely powerful. As a modern reader, it's hard not to be moved by Dante's poetry, even 7 centuries later, a fact that attests to the immortality of the work. Those who are unfamiliar with Dante and/or Italian Literature and stop reading the Commedia after the Inferno are missing out big time! I personally think the Paradiso is relatively boring, but for the more pious readers it can also be heart-stopping at times. <br /><br />My favorite part of the Purgatorio is canti 29-31 (and slightly beyond), wherein Dante glimpses his beloved for the first time in decades on the banks of the river Lethe. As she unveils her face, her organic beauty is so radiant that the pilgrim is nearly blinded by her, and he weeps as she scolds him for straying in his devotion to her after her passing. Her arrival is accompanied by a magnificent triumphal procession, meant to symbolize the Church; some scholars argue that Beatrice also serves the same function. The triumphal chariot is pulled by a gryphon - obviously a symbol of Jesus Christ.<br /><br />I'm currently working toward my doctoral degree in Early Modern (Medieval/Renaissance) Italian Literature, and it seems as though every time I take a course on Dante or lyric poetry or even Boccaccio and Petrarch (the other two "Crowns" that make up the famous "tre corone" of the Italian canon), I can't help but write about some part or another of the Purgatorio. Whether it's Ulysse's prideful, unnecessary death, or Beatrice's unveiling, or the triumphal chariots as a motif in the literature of the time period, I find myself coming back to the strangely familiar words of Dante like a comfort food. Dante mentions - and I can't remember exactly where just now - that even some of the worst sinners in the hour, minute, second of their death need only murmur even the name of Mary to be considered for admission into Purgatory (I'm getting this wrong, probably. Comps are coming up soon and I'll get it down pat eventually.) If you choose to read the Commedia in order - as you should - the Purgatorio is quite refreshing after making it through Inferno, yet the messages are still stern enough to get the reader to pay mind to his every action in this life. I'd be lying if I said some of the episodes, antiquated now as they may be, didn't affect some of my own personal decisions or renew the beautiful aspects of my Catholic upbringing.<br /><br />I also highly recommend this edition of the text (by Durling and Martinez). The whole Commedia is rife with allegorical references, so a good edition is key to understanding it fully and maximizing your Dante experience!</span>
  <a data-text-id="12843217814523454280" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

