<div id="review_48040050" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/48040050" />
    <a title="Jon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/929592-jon"><img alt="Jon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1212291234p2/929592.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/48040050?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jon" href="/user/show/929592-jon">Jon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385497008" href="/book/show/208472.Purgatorio">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer48040050" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4095979796750991532">I&apos;m apparently reading the Divine Comedy backwards this time, since I finished the Paradiso on Dec 31, and then read this one for our church faith exploration book club. This is probably the edition I would recommend to anybody trying the Comedy--the notes are thorough (maybe too thorough) and usually to the point. Hollander does not suffer fools gladly, though, and his dismissal of other scholars can be a bit abrupt. The translation is sometimes quite wonderful, and as far as I can tell, accura</span>
  <span id="freeText4095979796750991532" style="display:none">I'm apparently reading the Divine Comedy backwards this time, since I finished the Paradiso on Dec 31, and then read this one for our church faith exploration book club. This is probably the edition I would recommend to anybody trying the Comedy--the notes are thorough (maybe too thorough) and usually to the point. Hollander does not suffer fools gladly, though, and his dismissal of other scholars can be a bit abrupt. The translation is sometimes quite wonderful, and as far as I can tell, accurate. This is the first time I actually felt some of the responses that a reader of Italian is supposed to feel--the immense relief of cool, fresh, bright openness in the first canto, after the horrible darkness, pressure, and claustrophobia of the Inferno. The huge surprise when Dante finally actually meets his beloved Beatrice in the Earthly Paradise, and finds her not at all what he (or the reader) expected. Very interesting to read this while listening to <u>Acedia and Me</u>, since the mountain of Purgatory is all about washing away the effects of the seven deadly sins. Kathleen Norris' references to Dante are fairly good, but her understanding of acedia is not at all what his was.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4095979796750991532" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


