  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_299081251" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/299081251" />
    <a title="Zach Pickens" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1329437-zach-pickens"><img alt="Zach Pickens" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/299081251?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zach Pickens" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zach Pickens" href="/user/show/1329437-zach-pickens">Zach Pickens</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer299081251" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7683438221043846991">After trekking through the depths of hell, Dante, led by his guide and literary father Virgil, ascends the seven storied mountain of purgatory. Like hell, the souls’ torments fit the sins that engaged them in life, but unlike hell, the shades are not so much punished as they are purging themselves of the capital sins. Virgil and Dante reach the pinnacle of the mountain, the Garden of Eden, where Virgil departs leaving Dante with his next guide, Dante’s great love, Beatrice.<br/>A few thoughts:<br/><b>Virgil </b></span>
  <span id="freeText7683438221043846991" style="display:none">After trekking through the depths of hell, Dante, led by his guide and literary father Virgil, ascends the seven storied mountain of purgatory. Like hell, the souls’ torments fit the sins that engaged them in life, but unlike hell, the shades are not so much punished as they are purging themselves of the capital sins. Virgil and Dante reach the pinnacle of the mountain, the Garden of Eden, where Virgil departs leaving Dante with his next guide, Dante’s great love, Beatrice.<br />A few thoughts:<br /><b>Virgil in hell</b><br />What seems unjust to many commentators is Dante’s placement of Virgil in hell, especially notable because Dante believes that Virgil’s poetry was wise enough to contain a spark or the spirit of Christianity even before Christ. For example, the poet Statius credits Virgil’s writing with his turn to Christianity. According to the wonderful website DanteWorlds published by the University of Texas at Austin, Dante was in a tradition of medieval scholars who believed that Virgil was a forefather of Christianity—Virgil is writing before Christ’s birth, but his work is incorporated into the literary genealogy of Christian Rome. There are even a few pre-Christian pagans existing outside of hell—one in purgatory, two in paradise, but even at the end of the poem, it is clear that Virgil will not be joining them. <br /><br />Virgil does not argue against the seemingly unfair set of rules that keeps him in limbo. At one point in hell, when Dante is weeping over the horrible punishments, Virgil chastises him saying (I’m paraphrasing) Hey, this is all just part of God’s divine justice—everything is as it should be according to the supreme Good, so stop crying and grow up. I wonder if this is how Virgil sees his own fate. I wonder if there is wisdom in his acceptance of the divine, immutable law that keeps him in hell—acceptance as opposed to fighting what cannot be fought. Why argue? It’d be like disagreeing with the law of gravity. <br /><br />He also might be a victim of his allegorical status as “Reason.” Raymond Schoder, in an older article in The Classical Journal, defends Dante’s placement of Virgil in hell because, allegorically, the poem wouldn’t work otherwise; there is a place where “Reason” alone can go no further and where faith and love complete us. In Dante’s epic poem, this place is the Garden of Eden, where Virgil is replaced with Beatrice. <br /><br /><b>Virgil’s humanity</b><br />Virgil is dutiful (a characteristic prized by Rome and exemplified by Virgil’s Aeneas). But it is his dutifulness mixed with the rigidity of Dante’s universe that also gives Virgil’s character the sense of someone subverted; but this makes sense, not only because it is Dante’s journey, not Virgil’s, but also because Limbo is still a place without hope, and wisdom without hope still makes those shades languid. In Limbo, where Virgil abides, there is a “meadow of fresh verdure” where the greatest of the shades live. But the shades speak softly, and move slowly. They are forever left with desire unfulfilled; they are without hope. <br /><br />For me, this hopelessness is poignantly at odds with the humanity Virgil displays. Canto I ends with a beautiful exchange between Virgil and Dante: as the sun rises over the plain where they are walking, Virgil bends down and softly places his hands in the dewy grass and then uses that water to clean the tears from Dante’s face. Allegorically, this is “Reason” washing away the sins in preparation for the journey of purgation. But at the literal surface, the gesture and the physical sensation of it is touching. This is a poet who has spent over thirteen hundred years in a place without hope, without the earthly sun, without the morning dew. He must remember what it felt like to have the sun warm his face, the sound of the ocean at his side, the feel of the fresh grass beneath his feet. True, limbo isn’t as terrible as the other circles of hell—Virgil stays with the other poets in a place “open, luminous, and high,” but I imagine this does not compare with the nature of the living world. <br /><br />Like most people, I know the pleasant sensation of placing my hands in the cool dew that has collected on the blades of grass, of letting my hands brush against the clean blades. It feels cleansing. And so when Virgil places his hands in the cool wet grass in the morning sun, I wonder if he feels any hope contained in that nature. I wonder if he can keep some of that dew for himself. As someone who has been so long under the earth, as a poet who is able to take the sensations of the world and use them to express some greater meaning, how can this fail to touch him? The sun is rising. It is Easter, a time for resurrection and renewal. To wash the tears of someone’s face is an act of kindness--even love--that must come from a place very human, despite the abridgment of humanity in Limbo. To complete this gesture—to give comfort like this—is moving.<br /><br /><b>Beatrice in Canto XXX</b><br />After the divine instruction along the ascent to the top of purgatory, the appearance of Beatrice allegorically marks the transition from Reason to the Divine love and faith that accompanies true understanding. Outside of allegory, the experience of meeting Beatrice melts the ice around his heart, leaving him without any protection. Beatrice rebukes him—she is “like an admiral….” Noticing that Virgil has vanished, Dante starts to weep and Beatrice tells him to cease weeping for Virgil’s absence, for “it behooves thee to weep by another sword.” Loosely—I’ll give you something to cry about. <br /><br />I found this initial interaction very powerful. If this was a movie, the set would dim and go silent. This is not a pleasant reuniting; she lays out his sins frankly, with stern pity. Purgatory, indeed heaven and hell are all places where one cannot hide, cannot lie, or pretend. Every fact, deed, and thought of the living get sorted out in the uncompromising Truth of the afterlife—one’s sins are on display, which is shameful—Dante cannot stand to see his reflection in the water while Beatrice speaks to him. I think it’s fitting that this occurs in the Garden of Eden because he is essentially denuded, forced to see himself as he really is. Dante must truly walk through the fire, must face his sins—his turning away from her, from salvation. <br /><br />Perhaps because this scene comes after so much climbing--so much instruction with example of example of sin and repentance, it has the effect of a powerful transition, an emotional break with everything that has come before it. Dante has spent sixty three Cantos dutifully learning with Virgil, but he is utterly broken after a few words with his love Beatrice. <br /> <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7683438221043846991" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

